import streamlit as st

st.markdown("""
The worst part about grief is that it you will survive it. Despite your best intentions, you will be ok. Because the act of enduring something requires that it not kill you. One day you will wake up not sad. The quiet morning greets you. For a moment, you feel a sense of peace you haven’t felt in a long time, and you find yourself wishing the world would burn at least a little bit. Each moment you are alive takes you another second away from when and where they were last. The distance between you grows ever infinitely great; you have no choice but to heal. One day, you will wake up ok and realize it is not the loss that hurt you. It is the moving on.
""")

st.markdown("""
Grief feels strangely familiar. I imagine it’s the same feeling I get as a child when my dad would turn the corner and disappear from view, and I would cry as all children do before they learn object permanence. I imagine it’s the same thing happening now; this distress might only last until he comes back into view once more, and then we will laugh at the drama endured during our brief time apart. Maybe all this suffering is unnecessary and childish, and humans simply exist in the developmental period just before spiritual permanence. How silly we must appear to those who outgrew this life.
Why should this be my first life, and your last? Why couldn’t this be our millionth life together, having spent the previous eternity in each other’s company? There is no evidence nor reason that anything which happens now, must not have happened before or yet ever again. In any reality where there exists a One and The Other, there exists a Me and You.
So while you are away, before I can understand that objects exist beyond my senses, I’ll look for you in my memories, in the crowds, and in all the days that come after, so that when you come back into my sight, I will remember you and rejoice as if no time had passed at all.
""")

st.markdown("""
It is a fact of life that we lose everything we love in the end. It is the same fact by which we are graced: we do not live our lives at the end. We live in the beginning and everything between; what happens at the end is frankly none of our business.
""")
